0.title: Gleam

10.body:
A Bool can be either True or False . Gleam defines a handful of operators that work with Bools. False && False // => False
False && True // => False
True && False // => False
True && True // => True False || False // => False
False || True // => True
True || False // => True
True || True // => True && and || are short circuiting , meaning they don't evaluate the right hand side if they don't have to. && evaluates the right hand side if the left hand side is True . || evaluates the right hand side if the left hand side is False .

12.body: Gleam's main number types are Int and Float.

Floats are " real " numbers, meaning they have a decimal point. 1.5
2.0

14.title: Floats

15.body:
Tuples are an ordered collection of elements of a fixed size. Each element can be of a different type. The syntax for tuples in Gleam is the same as in Elixir and Erlang. // Gleam
{1, 2.0, "three"} # Elixir
true
{1, 2.0, "three"} % Erlang
{1, 2.0, <<"three">>}.
15.title: Tuples

16.body:
Lists are ordered collections of values. They're one of the most common data structures in Gleam. Lists are homogeneous , meaning all the elements of a List must be of the same type. Attempting to construct a list of multiple types of element will result in the compiler presenting a type error. // Gleam
[1, 2, 3, 4] // List(Int)
[1.22, 2.30] // List(Float)
[1.22, 3, 4] // Type error! Prepending to a list is very fast, and is the preferred way to add new values. // Gleam
[1 | [2, 3]] // => [1, 2, 3]
16.title: List

17.body:
A value can be given a name using let . Names can be reused by later let bindings, but the values contained are immutable , meaning the values themselves cannot be changed. // Gleam
let x = 1
let x = 2 # Elixir
x = 1
x = 2 % Erlang
X = 1.
X = 2. % Runtime error! Erlang doesn't allow rebinding Pattern matching can be used to extract contained values from data structures when defining variables with let . // Gleam
let {x, y} = {1, 2.0} # Elixir
{x, y} = {1, 2.0} % Erlang
{X, Y} = {1, 2.0}.

2.body: An expressive type system inspired by the ML family of languages helps us find and prevent bugs at compile time, long before it reaches your users. For the problems the type system can't solve (such as your server being hit by a bolt of lightning) the Erlang/OTP runtime provides well tested mechanisms for gracefully handling failure.
2.title: Be safe

20.body:
At runtime enum variants with no contained values become atoms. The atoms are written in snake_case rather than CamelCase so LoggedIn becomes logged_in . Enum variants with contained values become tuples with a tag atom. // Gleam
Guest
LoggedIn("Kim") # Elixir
:guest
{:logged_in, "Kim"} % Erlang
guest.
{logged_in, <<"Kim">>}.
20.title: Runtime representation

3.body: Hunting down bugs can be stressful so feedback from the compiler should be as clear and helpful as possible. We want to spend more time working on our application and less time looking for typos or deciphering cryptic error messages. As a community we want to be friendly too. People of all backgrounds, genders, and experience levels are welcome and must receive equal respect.
3.title: Be friendly

4.body: The Erlang/OTP runtime is known for its speed and ability to scale, enabling organisations such as WhatsApp and Ericsson to reliably handle massive amounts of traffic at low latency. Gleam should take full advantage of this runtime and be as fast as other BEAM languages such as Erlang and Elixir.
4.title: Be performant

5.body: Gleam makes it easy to use code written in other BEAM languages such as Erlang, Elixir and LFE, so there's a rich ecosystem of tools and library for Gleam users to make use of. Users of other BEAM languages should in return be able to take advantage of Gleam, either by transparently making use of libraries written in Gleam, or by adding Gleam modules to their existing project with minimal fuss.
5.title: Be a good citizen

6.body: Being another functional language on the BEAM (the Erlang virual machine) Gleam is very similar to both Erlang and Elixir, albeit with a static type system. This chapter aims to give Erlang and Elixir users enough knowledge to start writing reading and writing Gleam code.
6.title: Comparison to Erlang and Elixir

8.body:
Gleam's Strings are binary strings, the same as Elixir's strings. // Gleam
"Hello, Gleam!" # Elixir
"Hello, Elixir!" % Erlang
<<"Hello, Erlang!">>.
